7. Qd2 {This is the most popular move with which White is preparing the
so-called English attack. White plans to castle long and then expand on the
kingside with the moves f3 and g4. With knowledge of the ideas and some
concrete variations, practice has shown that Black can reach a comfortable
position in all variations.} Nf6 {The other options on move 7 for Black are a
bit dubious, but here Black doesn't have to avoid the main lines.} (7... b5 8.
O-O-O Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bb7 10. e5 {Black didn't solve the opening problems
completely.}) (7... Be7 {The idea is to avoid some sidelines and transpose to
the main line, however, it also allows several unpleasant possibilities.} 8.
Nxc6 $5 (8. g4 $5 {Is an extra option for White with this move order.}) (8.
O-O-O Nf6 {This is Black's idea.})) 8. O-O-O (8. f4 {Creates the positional
threat of e4-e5, so Black has to take action immediately.} Bb4 {The most
reliable move for Black, immediately creating the threat of Nxe4.} (8... b5 9.
e5 b4 {This counter-attacking move is available now.} (9... Ng4 10. Bg1 Bb7 11.
O-O-O Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Be7 13. Kb1 $36 {White has pressure down the d-file and is
ready to expand on the kingside.}) 10. Ncb5 {Black isn't doing very well at
the end of this line and the position is a bit unpleasant.} axb5 11. Nxb5 Qb8
12. exf6 gxf6 13. a4 {White supports the knight on b5, although this move
slightly weakens the pawn structure on the queenside but that's irrelevant
since White plans to castle on the kingside.} bxa3 14. bxa3 $14) 9. Bd3 {
Black has a choice between two approaches, one which is solid and leads a to
very slightly better position for White with a lot of drawish tendencies,
while the other one is more risky.} (9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. e5 Nd5 $13) 9... b5
{This is the more active and riskier approach.} (9... Na5 {This is the solid
approach. Black's idea isn't to capture on c3, but to play Nc4 instead.} 10. a3
Bxc3 11. Qxc3 (11. bxc3 {Trying to keep the queens on the board doesn't give
White anything.} b5 12. e5 Nd5 $15 {Black's knights are very good while
White's bishop pair isn't doing much in the position.}) 11... Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 {
Now Black has to play actively and accurately.} d5 13. exd5 {This is the
critical line.} (13. e5 Ne4 {Black's bishop is passive on c8, but in return,
the knights are very active.} 14. Nb3 Nc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Na5 Bd7 17. Bd4 (
17. Nxb7 Bc6 $11) (17. Nxc4 Rc8 {White needs to be careful not to end up in a
worse position.}) 17... Rc8 {Here, White has tried different options but they
don't give White anything and in fact, White has to be careful not to end up
in an inferior position.} 18. O-O-O (18. Rb1 b5 19. Ke2 (19. Rd1 f5 20. exf6
gxf6 21. O-O Rg8 22. Rfe1 f5 $11) 19... Ke7 20. Rbd1 f5 21. exf6+ gxf6 $11) (
18. Nxb7 Bc6 19. Na5 Bd5 {The bishop on d5 is active and restricts the passive
knight on a5 very well.} 20. Rb1 Kd7 21. Ke2 f5 $132 22. Ke3 h6 23. h4 $6 g5
$15 {[%eval 0,0] Sevian - Potkin, Wijk aan Zee 2015}) 18... b6 $1 19. Rhe1 {
19.Bxb6 can be met with 19... Nxc3.} bxa5 20. Rxe4 Bc6 21. Re2 Bd5 $11 {
Shirov - Movsesian, Loo 2014}) 13... exd5 {This is the better recapture for
Black.} (13... Nxd5 {Capturing with the knight on d5 doesn't solve all Black's
problems.} 14. Bd2 Nb6 15. Rb1 Nbc4 {Black can try to establish a knight on
the c4-square but it's only temporary.} 16. Rb4 Nxd2 17. Kxd2 {White doesn't
