tempo.}) 16. g5 Nh5 17. Qxd7 Qa5 $1 18. Qxb7 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Qxc3 {With the
bishop on f2, this line works.} 20. Bd3 Qb4+ $11 {White has to accept a draw
by perpetual check.} 21. Kc1 $2 Nf4 $1 $17 {This is a major difference between
Be3 and Bf2, White's dark-squared bishop is not controlling the f4-square.})
15... b4 (15... Bb4 {This move doesn't work very well for Black.} 16. g5 Nh5
17. Qxd7 Qa5 $2 {This is an interesting tactical try but it doesn't work for
Black.} 18. Qxb7 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Qxc3 20. Bd3 {White's king can escape from a
perpetual check, so White has a winning position.}) 16. Nd5 (16. Na4 d5 {
And now} 17. g5 {runs into:} d4 {This is a good intermediate move for Black,
hitting the bishop on e3 with tempo.}) 16... Nxd5 17. exd5 Bc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5
19. Rg2 d6 $132 {Black has solved all the opening problems and has a clear
plan of advancing the a-pawn, while it's not so clear how White will advance
on the kingside without creating weaknesses. The position is around equal but
White is the one that needs to be more careful in order to keep the balance.} *

