Biel 1985}) (9. Qd2 Nf6 {White's queen isn't controlling the g4-square anymore,
so the knight can jump there if needed.} 10. e5 (10. O-O-O Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b4 12.
Bxf6 (12. Na4 Bxe4) 12... gxf6 13. Ne2 a5 $15 {This position is a version
similar to a Sicilian Rauzer variation where Black's king feels safe on the
e8-square while White's king is going to be under attack.}) 10... Ng4 11. Bg1
Nxd4 12. Bxd4 d6 $5 $146 {Black breaks in the center and even though at first
sight it may seem that Black's king is vulnerable in the center, it's not the
case.} (12... O-O-O $2 13. h3 Nh6 14. Qf2 {This is unpleasant for Black.}) 13.
Qe2 (13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. Qe2 dxe5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. fxe5 Bb4 {Black is doing
very well in this position.} 17. Be4 Bxc3 18. Bxb7+ Kxb7 19. Qf3+ Qc6 20. Qxf7+
Kb8 21. bxc3 Qxc3) 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 O-O-O $1 {This is a very good tactical
resource.} 15. Qxg4 h5 16. Qf4 g5 {Black will win back the minor piece.} 17.
Qf6 (17. Qe3 $6 Rxd4) 17... Rh6 18. Qxg5 Rxd4 19. O-O-O Rg4 20. Qd2 Rh8 {
Black's pieces are very active and White has to play accurately.} 21. Kb1 Rxg2
22. Qe1 Rg5 $132) (9. Qe2 {Black doesn't have the g4-square available so there
won't be a good follow-up after Nf6, but now Black can win the f4-pawn instead.
} Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Qxf4 11. Rf1 Qxh2 {Black is ready to castle queenside if
needed and White doesn't have enough time to create some dangerous threats.}
12. O-O-O Ne7 $13) (9. O-O Bc5 {If White castles immediately, this typical
resource is unpleasant to face with White.}) 9... Na5 $5 {The knight heads to
the c4-square.} (9... Nf6 10. O-O) 10. Nxa5 (10. O-O Nc4 11. Bd4 (11. Bc1 Nf6
12. Qe2 (12. e5 b4 {This is a good way to meet e4-e5 in this position.}) 12...
Bb4 $15 {Levy - Portisch, Hastings 1970}) (11. Bxc4 bxc4 (11... Qxc4 12. Na5
Qc7 13. Nxb7 Qxb7 14. a3 {Black is behind in development, so it's better to
recapture with the pawn on move 11.}) 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. Rad1 Be7 $11
{Andersson - Krnic, Sombor 1970}) 11... Ne7 {Black doesn't need to rush since
the bishop on d4 can be vulnerable to attack. Black intends to play Nc6 next.}
(11... Nxb2 {Black shouldn't be greedy because after:} 12. Qe2 Nxd3 13. cxd3
$13 {White will place a rook on c1 and the position can become quite
unpleasant for Black.}) 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. Nc5 Nf5 $5 {This is a nice tactical
resource for Black.} 14. Nxb7 (14. Nxe6 $6 dxe6 15. exf5 O-O-O {White might
get in trouble very soon.}) (14. Nxa6 Rxa6 15. exf5 exf5 {The rook is ready to
protect the Black king with Re6, so Black doesn't have any problems in the
position.}) 14... Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Rb8 {This is an interesting idea, the queen
doesn't capture the knight and remains on the better c7-square.} 16. e5 Rxb7
17. Ne4 Be7 $11) 10... Qxa5 11. O-O (11. a3 Qc7 12. O-O Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 14.
Kh1 Ne7 $11) 11... b4 12. Nb1 Bc5 $146 {Black will manage to complete the
